ty Worlds reflects the authors’ anthropological commitments to recognizing the significance of this fundamental form of human difference. Ginsburg and Rapp’s conversations with diverse New Yorkers reveal the bureaucratic constraints and paradoxes established in response to the disability rights movement, as well as the remarkable creativity of disabled people and their allies who are opening pathways into both disability justice and disability futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChildren with disabilitiesxServices forzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aDisability awarenesszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aDisability culture. 0aDisability studies. 0aNeurodiversity. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxPolitical activityzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aRapp, Rayna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059394?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059394/original  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles